[normal]Evaluation[bold] of [bold]the ‘inclusiveness’ [bold]of existing[bold] [bold]education [bold]sector plans[bold] –
[normal] 
[normal]the Monitoring and Evaluation 
[normal](M&amp;E) team of the G
[normal]PE Secretariat is conducting a comprehensive 
[normal]evaluation of member countries’ edu
[normal]cation sector plans.  The evaluation
[normal] includes an equity dimension that assesses, for example, whether sector plans address education for children with special needs.
[normal] It will inform improvements to sector monitoring and help to identify data gaps
[normal]. 
[normal]The evaluation is expected 
[normal]to be concluded by
[normal] mid-2014. 
[normal]Previous analyses 
[normal]indicate s
[normal]ector plans in a number of 
[normal]G
[normal]PE – endorsed countries
[normal] i
[normal]nclude specific strategies
[normal] to target childre
[normal]n
[normal] with special needs, and
[normal] 
[normal]deta
[normal]iled 
[normal]a
[normal]ctivities and timelines
[normal].  
[normal]Guyana[bold]’s[bold] education sector plan, for exampl
[normal]e, includes 
[normal]specific activities such as conducting a national study to determine the number of 
[normal]students with special needs as well as 
[normal]creating special resource centers
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Similarly, 
[normal]Ethiopia[bold] has adopted a strategy for special needs education within its education sector 
[normal]program.
[normal] 
