[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Direct support for[bold] [bold]children with special needs[bold] [bold]- [bold]s
[normal]everal GPE
[normal] grants 
[normal]directly 
[normal]finance 
[normal]education activities 
[normal]for children with special needs
[normal]. 
[normal]In
[normal] 
[normal]Cambodia[bold], 
[normal]for example, 
[normal]a GPE grant of US
[normal] 
[normal]$
[normal]57.4 million for the period 2008-2012 
[normal]is supporting
[normal] the Ministry of Edu
[normal]cation and 
[normal]Youth 
[normal]to conduct a survey on the needs of marginalized and disabled children excluded from education. 
[normal]A total of 
[normal]13,175 children aged 11-15 were screened  in 56 elementary schools under t
[normal]he Out-of-School and Disability Survey
[normal], which used a state-of-the-art methodology for data collection and referring to services of children with disabilities and impairments, and provided them with ey
[normal]e 
[normal]glasses at the low cost of US
[normal] 
[normal]$
[normal]2 a pair. For the first time, the survey also provided high-q
[normal]uality data on disability and education, which enabled the Ministry to plan and budget for more targeted intervent
[normal]ions, and ultimately better addr
[normal]ess the issue of access to primary education for the most marginalized. As a result, the out-of-school populat
[normal]ion in Cambodia was halved between 2007 and 2011, a large part of which was due to a significant increase in the am
[normal]ount of disabled children 
[normal]able to attend school. Unde
[normal]r this initiative,
[normal] t
[normal]eachers from 56 schools were trained on 
[normal]vision testing so teachers 
[normal]can
[normal] assess 
[normal]whether children need
[normal] to be referred for refraction or for an eye exam. 
[normal]The results of the GPE-funded surv
[normal]ey were also shared with other
[normal] Ministries and development partners in Cambodia, prompting a number of education programs to support childre
[normal]n with disabilities and impairments. These initiatives range from inclusive teacher training, to disability awareness campaigns, and vision and hearing screenings for children in primary schools.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Similarly, 
[normal]Moldova[bold] is currently implementing a GPE grant 
[normal]of
[normal] US
[normal] 
[normal]$
[normal]4.4 million 
[normal]for the period 2012 to 2014, with the aim of
[normal] improving access, quality and inclusiveness of preschool education. 
[normal]The grant
[normal] is a continuation of two successfully comp
[normal]leted grants
[normal] implemented from 2006 to 2010
[normal]. 
[normal]Since 2006, 
[normal]GPE has provided 
[normal]Moldova with
[normal] 
[normal]technical assistance to revise
[normal] sanitary reforms and legislation encouraging inclusive approaches, as well as the promotion of integrated services across the education, health
[normal] and social protection sectors. 
[normal]Moldova 
[normal]has 
[normal]also developed key docume
[normal]nts promoting inclusiveness such as standards for learning and development of children (from birth to 7 years old), standards for pre-school teachers, and a guide on socio-educational inclusiveness of children with disabilities, and continues
[normal] to promote in
[normal]clusive approaches
[normal] through a broader teac
[normal]her training/mentoring program. 
[normal]With the support of GPE
[normal], 
[normal]two 
[normal]‘pilot’ 
[normal]centers 
[normal]have been established 
[normal]for 
[normal]the 
[normal]rehabilitation of children with special needs within mainstream kindergartens in Straseni and in Criuleni (respectively 15 and 24 children benefitted). 
[normal]More recently, GPE funding supported
[normal] the establishment of one additional rehabilitation center for child
[normal]ren with disabilities in Ceadir Lunga UTAG Gagauzia (61 beneficiaries), and 
[normal]there are 
[normal]plans are to create a similar center in Nisporeni (17 exp
[normal]ected beneficiaries). 
[normal]GPE support 
[normal]has also 
[normal]helped 
[normal]to 
[normal]leverage support from other partners, such as UNICEF and loc
[normal]al NGOs, for the inclusion of children with special needs in mainstream institutions.
