[normal]Support for children with special needs through the [bold]Global and Regional Activities [bold](GRA) Program[bold] 
[normal]- 
[normal]the GRA Program supports 
[normal]capacity development, knowledge sharing and knowledge development at the regional and global levels and is complementary to the country level process. It fosters innovation through the systematic provision of services and products that enlighten, engage, a
[normal]nd energize partners to apply new knowledge and evidence based good practices to resolve education challenges
[normal]. A proposal 
[normal]submitted by the World Bank 
[normal]was
[normal] approved 
[normal]in July 2013 
[normal]for 
[normal]US 
[normal]$3 million to im
[normal]prove the management of moderate disabilities of school-a
[normal]ge children through school based health interventions to ensure children, especially gi
[normal]rls,
[normal] complete primary education. T
[normal]he 
[normal]program aims to 
[normal]improve learning outcomes and access to education in 15 GPE developing partner countries
[normal], including 10 countries in 
[normal]Africa and 5 in Southeast Asia
[normal]. The program will address knowledge gaps in operational and technical understanding of disability and provide the support needed to include children with disabilities, impairments and untreated health conditions to prevent th
[normal]em from dropping out, and to improve access to education. 
[normal]The activity will be managed by the World Bank in cooperation with WHO, Sight Savers, Save the Children, Partnership for Child Development, Imperial College, Children Without Worms and national NGOs
[normal] will be involved at country level. 
